<p>Research on 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I> has a long history in Germany and  many individual 
research groups have been using this plant for analysis of 
specific topics in plant biology. Furthermore, individual 
groups and German members of the European sequencing 
consortia contributed to the analysis of the Genome structure 
and its sequencing. Functional 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Genome analysis has recently received strong support in 
Germany through the implementation of two major research 
programs supported by the 
<A HREF="http://www.bmbf.de/en/">
German Ministry for Education and Research
</A> (BMBF) and the 
<A HREF="http://www.dfg.de/english/">
German Research Foundation
</A> (DFG). The aims and the contents of these two programs 
will be presented in the following paragraphs.
</p>  
<p>In 1999, the German plant genome program 
<A HREF="http://www.gabi.de">
GABI
</A> was initiated with the aim of strengthening plant genome 
research in Germany, establishing a network of competence 
including public and private research groups and business 
companies, enhancing international collaboration, and 
enhancing transfer of knowledge into application. GABI is the 
acronym for "Genome Analysis in the Plant Biological System". 
The 
<A HREF="http://www.bmbf.de/en/">
German Ministry for Education and Research
</A> (ca. 90% contribution) and private business companies 
(ca. 10% contribution) provide the financial support for the 
GABI programme. Within the GABI initiative, ca. 50% of the 
total volume of about 50 million Euro spent through a period 
of 4 years are devoted to work on the model system 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I>. In GABI, a one-programme-thesis is followed with 
respect to plant genome research. The direct interlocking of 
research on the model organism(s) and the transfer of these 
results to crops plants is a fundamental principle of this 
initiative. 
<A HREF="http://www.gabi.de/neu/bekanntmachungen/index_e.html">
Established rules
</A> regulate the disclosure and the use of research results 
obtained though GABI activities.
</p>
<p>A major aim of GABI is the establishment and support of 
international co-operations. Development of a network that 
links the various national activities is of particular 
relevance in Europe owing to the splintered structure of the 
European research area. A first step towards setting up 
direct collaborative efforts in Europe are joint research 
projects between the French plant genome program, 
<A HREF="http://www.genoplante.org/">
G&#233;noplante
</A> and the German 
<A HREF="http://www.gabi.de/">
GABI
</A> initiative. Here, the model plant 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> serves as the frontrunner and provides a model for 
international cooperation. The first joint projects will 
start within this year.
</p> 
<p>In addition to the GABI program funded by the BMBF, 
another initiative taken about one year ago has attracted 
attention in Germany. The 
<A HREF=" http://www.dfg.de/english/">
Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft
</A> (DFG) - German Research Foundation - has set links to 
the US 
<A HREF="http://www.nsf.gov/">
National Science Foundation
</A> (NSF) in order to support in a co-ordinated fashion 
projects on 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> functional genome analysis. AFGN, the 
<A HREF="http://www.uni-frankfurt.de/fb15/botanik/mcb/AFGN/AFGNHome.html">

<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Functional Genomics Network
</A>, in order to achieve the enormous goal of elucidating 
the function of all 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genes within the next ten years. This will undoubtedly 
only be possible if further programmes / activities running or initiated in other countries will enter in and 
participate.
</p>


