<p>Subprojects:
</p>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>Generation of 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> and barley protein expression libraries and chips
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:kersten@molgen.mpg.de">
Birgit Kersten
</A>
<br>
<p>This Subproject will interdigitate with the 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> and 
<A HREF="http://www.gabi.de/projekte/bereich1/pjgseed_e.html">
GABI-Barley Seed community
</A> in generating extensive UNIgene/UNIprotein cDNA 
libraries for expressing HIS-tagged recombinant proteins in 
<I>E. coli
</I>. Optimal clones (which are full length, have the insert 
in the correct reading frame, no internal stop codon, etc.), 
corresponding to each gene will be selected by OFP analysis 
and immunoscreening. The arrayed libraries will be used to 
generate affinity-purified protein from each clone using high 
throughput automation: the proteins will in turn be spotted 
at high density onto membranes and latter at very high 
density onto glass (protein chips), providing a low-cost 
resource for in vitro studies of protein-protein and protein-
ligand interaction. The expression banks themselves will 
constitute a most useful resource in providing ready-made 
material for creating antibodies and MPF analyses. Clones 
which prove refractory to expression here will be handed to 
workers in other groups who have expertise in yeast and 
insect cell overexpression systems. The technology, once 
established in the laboratory, will be transferred to the 
Resource Centre and thereby made available to the scientific 
community.
</p>
</DD>
</DT>
</DL>
<LI>Mass spectrometric techniques for the analysis of plant 
proteomes suitable to accomplish service tasks
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:gobom@molgen.mpg.de">
Johan Gobom
</A>
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:joachim.klose@charite.de">
Joachim Klose
</A>
<br>
<p>This Subproject will develop high throughput methods for 
analysing plant proteins. The central methods are MALDI mass 
spectrometry large-format 2D electrophoresis. These 
technologies will be applied for analysing and characterising 
total proteomes from 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> and barley. In 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> this will be possible by generating theoretical peptide 
mass fingerprints (MPF's) for each gene products already 
available and matching them with the MPF from a particular 
2-DE spot. In barley we expect to be able to identify 
fingerprinted proteins in an analogous manner via the partial 
sequence information provided by EST and OFP data to be 
produced in collaboration with GABI-Seed, and by direct 
"Bridge" comparisons with mass spectrometric data of 
recombinant proteins from Subproject 1. High throughput 
sample preparation and subsequent MALDI-MS methods will be 
offered to the GABI community according to progress in our 
technique-development. At an appropriate stage, the 
technology will be transferred to the Resource Centre in the 
DHGP and thereby made available to the scientific community 
on a large scale.
</p>
</DD>
</DT>
</DL>
<LI>Identification of protein-protein interactions using an 
automated yeast two hybrid system
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:heyl@molgen.mpg.de">
Alexander Heyl
</A>
<br>
<p>This Subproject will exploit recent advances in Y2H-based 
methods for identifying protein-protein interactions in vivo. 
As it is now possible to eliminate autoactivating clones from 
the bait and the prey population, a high throughput procedure 
for screening protein-protein interactions involved in a 
number of key proteins in plant will be developed.  A matrix 
of protein-protein interactions will be generated and made 
accessible to the scientific community.
</p>
<p>In the first part of the project we plan to provide a 
service for the 
<I>Arabidopsis
