<p>
<IMG SRC="/images/redball.gif">
 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> network I: "Creation and Detection of New Genetic 
Diversity" 
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>Coordinator: 
<A HREF="mailto:altmann@mpimp-golm.mpg.de">
Thomas Altmann
</A>
</DD>
</DT>
</DL>
<p>In this network a range of new genetic variants, including 
homogenous novel genotypes, recombinant inbred lines and near 
isogenic lines derived from combinations of different 
accessions will be created. Another major aspect of the 
project is the development of a large collection of single 
nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), which will be identified in 
a diverse range of 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genotypes, and the implementation of tools for highly 
efficient and multi-parallel SNP monitoring. The new and 
highly efficient genetic marker systems thus established will 
strongly support gene / QTL mapping and, together with the 
technologies developed for (genome wide) mutation scanning, 
they will enhance the efficiency of map-based gene cloning 
approaches.
</p>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>Subproject: Creation of Novel Genetic Variants of 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I>
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:altmann@mpimp-golm.mpg.de">
Thomas Altmann
</A>
</DD>
</p>
<p>Establishment of new wild type varieties, F2 populations, 
recombinant inbred lines (RILs), and genetic substitution 
lines (near isogenic lines, NILs).
</p>
<p>This project is devoted to the generation of new genetic 
resources for the functional analysis of the 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I> genome. Main emphasis is put on the creation of genetic 
variants, which, besides loss-of-function mutations, may 
carry change-of-function and gain-of-function mutations. 
Recent work, e.g. on plant-pathogen interactions, flower 
induction, seed dormancy, physiological characteristics, and 
nutrient efficiency, provided clear evidence for the 
increasing importance of the analysis of natural genetic 
diversity developed under selective pressure. To provide the 
means to efficiently evaluate the genetic diversity provided 
by the large collection of available accessions (ecotypes), 
F2 populations will be generated from unified varieties 
propagated through a single seed passage. 20 "genotype A" x 
"genotype B" (reciprocal) combinations will be generated per 
year and F2 seeds will be bulked and distributed for 
evaluation by co-operating groups. Based on pre-existing 
experience and on information accumulated through the 
evaluation of the provided F2 populations, varieties will be 
selected for the generation of new recombinant inbred lines 
(RILs). Thus, single F2 progeny plants (about 400 per variety 
combination) will be propagated as single seed descents to 
the F8 generation. One "variety A" x "variety B" combination 
per year will be selected and processed. The resulting RILs 
will be amplified and genotyped by evaluation of at least 100 
genetic markers. This will primarily be done through 
application of the SNP-based marker systems developed in the 
accompanying project. The genotype data will be deposited and 
made available through the central databases, and the RILs 
will be distributed as seed stocks for specific phenotypic 
analysis by co-operating groups.
</p>
<p>An advanced level of evaluation of the genetic diversity 
provided by the various genotypes will be possible if only 
single short fragments are substituted between genotypes. 
Thus, for one selected genotype combination (C24 x Col), NILs 
will be generated from F1s by repeated back-crossing and 
monitoring of the genetic constitution. In is this way, a set 
of ca. 100 NILs will be created, each of which with a single 
substituted DNA segment of about 5 cM / 1.3 Mbp. Also this 
work will strongly be supported by the development of the 
SNP-based marker systems which provide the means for 
mulitplexed marker analysis. As for the RILs, the information 
on the genetic constitution will be deposited and made 
available through the central databases and the developed 
lines will be distributed as seed stocks.
</p>
</DT>
</DL>
<LI>Subproject: Establishment of high-efficiency SNP-based 
mapping tools and development of methods for genome-wide 
mutation detection
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:tmo@ice.mpg.de">
Thomas Mitchell-Olds
</A>
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:weisshaa@mpiz-koeln.mpg.de">
Bernd Weisshaar
</A>
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:altmann@mpimp-golm.mpg.de">
Thomas Altmann
</A>
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:soldatov@molgen.mpg.de">
Aleksey Soldatov
</A>
</DD>
</p>
<p>A very large fraction of genetic variants carry (point) 
mutations or other minor sequence variations that may lead to 
change of function or gain of function of the gene products. 
They constitute one of the most important classes of mutants 
for a functional genome analysis program. To support gene 
identification we will generate SNP markers and develop 
techniques for mutation detection / mutation scanning. Such a 
system can be applied to fine-mapping of induced mutations or 
QTLs.
<p>
<p>SNPs will be identified among several different 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I> genotypes. In this phase of the project, we will focus 
on 5 (6) varieties, namely Col-0, (Ler), Cvi, C24, Nd, and 
Ei-2 which are most frequently used as standard laboratory 
strains for mutagenesis experiments, genomic sequencing, set-
up of mapping populations and/or which have been selected on 
the basis of particularly great phenotypic or genotypic 
differences. Col-0 serves as the standard genotype per se. 
Using the 5 (6) varieties we will identify 1.300 SNPs. This 
set shall be composed of (1) a framework set of ca. 100 SNPs 
evenly spaced (in terms of physical distance) throughout the 
genome and (2) ca. 1,200 SNPs between the framework (SNP) 
markers to reach an average density of about 1 SNP per 100 
kb.
</p>
<p>To this end, ca. 100 evenly spaced sites (at about 1.3 Mbp 
distances) will be selected from the physical map / the 
genome sequence and 500 bp fragments will be PCR-amplified 
and (re-)sequenced for the different varieties. The 
participating groups will use complementary strategies, 
genomic re-sequencing and EST sequnecing to identify the 
additional large number of (randomly distributed) SNPs. The 
SNP information collected will be regularly exchanged between 
all partners and will be made available to other co-operating 
groups and to the public through a newly estblished SNP 
database and the central databases (PD by RZPD and 
GABIinfo).A novel SNP scoring technology developed and used 
to establish a multi-parallel, high efficiency SNP detection 
system. After implementation of the technology and cross-
validation of the scoring procedures, it will be transferred 
to the GABI Bioinformatics and Resource Centers for broad and 
general accessibility.
</p>
</DT>
</DL>
</UL>
<p>
