<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Network II: "Protein Communities in 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I>" 
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>Co-ordinators: 
<A HREF="mailto:Frommer@uni-tuebingen.de">
Wolf B. Frommer
</A> and 
<A HREF="mailto:bmr@rz.uni-potsdam.de)">
Bernd M&#252;ller-R&#246;ber
</A>
</DD>
</p>
<p>Projects in this network aim to achieve classification of 
the function of whole protein communities by genome-wide 
analyses. Starting with proteins of known or suspected 
functions, defined in a broad sense (e.g. membrane 
transporters, channels, plastid proteins, kinases, 
transcription factors), the corresponding gene or transcript 
information will be used to identify mutants in 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I>, or generate transgenic lines that are altered in the 
activity of these proteins. Combined biochemical and 
physiological analyses will then help to determine the true 
function of each protein and/or family of proteins. The 
projects in this network reflect the different protein 
communities. Interactions between proteins that are expected 
or uncovered during the project period will naturally lead to 
powerful co-operations between the various groups involved, 
and through sophisticated analyses will disclose and 
integrate novel protein functions.
</p>
<p>Protein communities will be addressed at:
<DD>- the level of compartmentation/ intracell- ular protein 
networks and
<br>- the level of transcriptional regulatory networks, which 
link different signal transduction cascades starting at the 
cellular membrane to the activity of genes.
</DD>
</p> 
<p>The proposed approaches will supply large pools of clones 
for studies on protein-protein as well as protein-DNA 
interactions, and they will employ a large spectrum of 
disciplines, including molecular genetics, biochemistry, 
genomics, proteomics, robotics and bioinformatics.
</p>
<p>Compared to the analyses of total genomic or transcribed 
information initiated world-wide, we see competitive 
advantage in establishing traps based on functional 
selection. With the laboratories collaborating in this 
network, the increasing importance and simultaneously 
increasing complexity of the analyses downstream of nucleic 
acid sequences is in the hands of internationally recognised 
experts and will provide a cutting edge in the world-wide 
activities.
</p>
<p>The consortium "Protein Communities" is embedded into the 
higher order 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Functional Genome Analysis project and is directly 
linked to the two other consortia "Genetic Diversity" and 
"Gauntlets".
</p>
</DT>
</DL>
<p>
<DT>Subprojects:
</p>
<dd>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>Identification and characterization of novel plant 
transport proteins using functional genomics approaches
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:ui.fluegge@uni-koeln.de">
Ulf-Ingo Fl&#252;gge
</A>
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:Frommer@uni-tuebingen.de">
Wolf B. Frommer
</A>
</DD>
<p>In most biochemical pathways solute transport into or out 
of a cell (or cell compartments) represents a strategic 
checkpoint for the metabolic state and development of a 
plant. This project focuses on functional genomics approaches 
leading to the identification, classification, and functional 
characterization of 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I> membrane proteins (plasma, plastidic, mitochondrial 
membranes and tonoplast) involved in sensing and transport. 
Many of these proteins will be critically involved in 
response and tolerance reactions of plants to environmental 
challenges (water-, salt-, temperature-stress, uptake of 
nutrients, chemical plant protection agents, pollutants, 
toxins, etc). Their functional characterization will pave the 
way for novel biotechnological applications in plant 
breeding, eventually enabling the development of 
agronomically important crop varieties with novel or improved 
properties.
</p>
<p>The experimental strategies followed include:
<OL TYPE=A>
<LI>
<I>in silico
</I> Transporter Gene Identification
<br>An important goal of this project is the identification 
and functional characterization of novel transporter 
proteins. Using a variety of bioinformatical tools (BLAST 
homology searches, hydrophobicity plots, etc.) we will scan 
the 
<A HREF="http://ukcrop.net/agr/">

<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Genome Database
</A> to identify putative novel membrane proteins having one 
or more membrane spanning domains. These candidates appearing 
from this scanning procedure will be compared to known 
membrane proteins and classified, thereby enabling us to make 
a meaningful priority decision about which proteins will be 
functionally characterized in detail.
<LI>Functional Complementation of Yeast Mutants
<br>Yeast complementation has been the breakthrough 
technology for the identification and analysis of plant 
transporters for sugars, amino acids and peptides. In yeast, 
an even broader variety of membrane transporters has been 
identified and characterized. Several mutants with uptake 
deficiencies are already available, and the collection of 
deletion strains of all yeast reading frames is scheduled for 
completion by the end of the year 1999 (EUROFAN). We will 
select putative transport mutants from this collection, and, 
as the identification of exporters and internal membrane 
transporters requires retargeting of proteins, will construct 
uptake mutants carrying multiple deletions by sequential 
homologous recombination. Biochemical specificities of 
respective proteins and physiological characteristics of 
mutant strains will be investigated, enabling us to establish 
appropriate selection conditions for functional 
complementation using 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> full length cDNA libraries in yeast expression vectors 
to identify novel transporters (e.g. for various solutes 
including ureides, nucleobases, inositol, ascorbate etc.).
<LI>Multiplex Expression Analysis
<br>Tailored cDNA arrays will be developed that contain a 
collection of membrane transport protein and control genes of 
which non-conserved cDNA fragments 200-400 bp in length will 
be amplified. With these cDNA arrays we will investigate the 
physiological plant response to environmental stress 
conditions and nutritional deficiencies at the level of 
transcriptional regulation of genes involved in transport 
processes. In establishing growth conditions we will closely 
adhere to standards that are being defined by international 
microarray initiatives and collaborate with the "Gauntlet" 
consortium within GABI. In addition, we will determine the 
global membrane protein gene expression levels in selected 
knock-out mutants.
<LI>Functional characterization by mutant analysis
<br>Phenotypical and physiological consequences of knock-out 
mutations will be investigated in detail, thereby allowing 
evaluation of potential agronomic applications in crop plant 
species. T-DNA and transposable element-induced large 
populations of insertion mutants made available by the 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> stock centers (
<A HREF=".uk/">
NASC
</A> and 
<A HREF="/abrc/">
ABRC
</A>) will be used to perform reverse genetics screenings for 
knock-out mutations of novel transporter genes.
<LI>Analysis of substrate specificity and transport activity
<br>To characterize substrate specificity and transport 
activity, putative membrane transporter genes will be 
expressed in 
<I>Xenopus
</I> oocytes. For the selected genes full-length cDNAs will 
be isolated and cloned into GFP-fusion expression vectors. 
The GFP-moiety will allow the non-destructive "on line" 
expression monitoring. Transport characteristics will be 
determined by measurement of membrane potential changes 
(TEVC).
</OL>
</DT>
</DL>
<LI>Transcription factor function search: How do individual 
factors regulate agronomically important processes in plants?
<DL>
<DT>
<DD>
<A HREF="mailto:bmr@rz.uni-potsdam.de">
Bernd M&#252;ller-R&#246;ber
</A>
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:weisshaa@mpiz-koeln.mpg.de">
Bernd Weisshaar
</A>
<br>
<p>Transcription factors (TFs) contribute considerably to the 
expression of traits of agronomic and biotechnological 
importance in higher plants. In the model 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I> a systematic analysis will be performed in order to 
determine which genes are regulated by which TFs. In total 
about 300 TFs will be studied in tight co-ordination between 
the partners: 200 by the group in Golm (
<A HREF="mailto:bmr@rz.uni-potsdam.de">
Bernd M&#252;ller-R&#246;ber
</A>, 
<A HREF="http://www.mpimp-golm.mpg.de/">
MPI-MP
</A>, Golm) and 100 by the group in Cologne (
<A HREF="mailto:weisshaa@mpiz-koeln.mpg.de">
Bernd Weisshaar
</A>, 
<A HREF="http://www.mpiz-koeln.mpg.de/">
MPI-Z
</A>, Cologne). To determine the functions of the selected 
members of large TF gene families, over-expression lines will 
be generated and null-mutants will be isolated. The proposed 
TF function deduced from the phenotype of these plants will 
be verified or falsified through physiological, molecular, 
and/or morphological analysis of the overexpressing or 
null-mutant plants. The further aim of this project is the 
use of the created data to identify TF genes that modulate 
agronomical important characteristics of plants.
</p>
</DD>
