<p>This network aims to identify genes that play a crucial 
role in determining how the model plant 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I> responds to a wide range of abiotic and biotic factors, 
and analyse how they interact to determine fitness and 
productivity.
<OL TYPE=i>
<LI>A wide range of defined growth conditions ("gauntlets") 
will be established in which the response to different carbon 
balances, nutrient limitation, anaerobiosis, temperature, pH, 
salt, water and heavy metal stress, and biotic stress are 
clearly, reproducibly and controllably displayed.
<LI>High-throughput techniques will be exploited to analyse 
transcript-, protein/enzyme activity-, peptide-, 
oligosaccharide-, and metabolite-profiles. Emphasis will be 
placed on generation of validated results in defined 
conditions that are suitable for integration and exploration 
in a multi-dimensional data bank. Interpretation of 
transcript and metabolite profiles will be supported by a 
characterisation of the sources of variation in individual 
transcripts and metabolites in non-stressed material, and by 
investigation of developmental-, tissue- and cell-specific 
transcript, protein and metabolite profiles. Working against 
this growing background of information:
<LI>Genes, proteins, peptides and metabolites involved in 
sensing and/or responding to environmental challenges will be 
isolated using complementary approaches, including non-biased 
horizontal analysis of transcripts and metabolites, and 
mutant screening based on novel phenotypes or expression 
patterns. 
<LI>Groups of genes, proteins/enzyme activities and 
metabolites will be identified that are diagnostic for 
different states.
<LI>Transformants with altered expression of candidate genes 
will be subjected to systematic analysis to provide a 
detailed analysis of gene function.
</OL>
<p>The aim of this consortium is a systematic functional 
analysis that encompasses all the genes in the genome to be 
achieved by combining
<OL TYPE=i>
<LI>the unique genetic resources made available by the 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genome project with 
<LI>what is termed "gauntlets" - high throughput test systems 
to detect changes in behaviour and fitness in response to 
various environmental challenges, and
<LI>emerging technologies that allow high throughput analyses 
of transcripts, proteins, peptides, oligosaccharides, and 
metabolites. The goal is a thorough analysis of a model 
system in multiple dimensions: genetic constitution 
(loss-of-function and gain-of-function mutants, ecotypes and 
ecotype combinations), conditions (various environmental 
factors), space (organs, tissues and cell types), and time 
(developmental status). 
</OL>
<p>This will provide the means to uncover important genetic 
diversity and identify novel candidate genes for use in 
breeding, to identify key gene programmes and key regulatory 
metabolites, and to identify transcript, proteins/enzyme 
activity and metabolite sets that can be employed as 
diagnostic kits for physiological states or genetic 
predispositions.The approach taken in this network integrates 
a wide range of approaches and contains novel and unique 
features:
</p>
<p>First, selection of the growth conditions and plant 
phenotype is given a high priority, because the need for 
correct choice of the experimental conditions is not relaxed 
when analytic techniques become more efficient: on the 
contrary, it becomes even more important because otherwise 
massive amounts of suspect or ill-defined data will 
accumulate and hold back progress. By interacting with 
specialists in bioinformatics, both locally and in 
<A HREF="http://mips.gsf.de/proj/gabi/">
GABI-Info
</A>, the participants will exploit their experience to set 
up robust and reliable central multi-dimensional data bank 
that includes guidelines for the design and validation of 
experiments whose results are to be submitted to the data 
bank.
</p>
<p>Second, the network unites groups with experience in, or 
with privileged access to, novel analytic techniques and 
developments: this includes not only arrays for 
multi-parallel transcript analysis, but also the powerful 
high throughput techniques for analysis of proteins 
oligosaccharides, peptides and metabolites, including a broad 
spectrum of secondary metabolites. A further important 
feature is the application of these techniques at the tissue 
and single cell level. This comprehensive analysis of 
responses at the levels of overall growth and visual 
phenotype, transcripts, protein/enzyme activities, and 
metabolites will allow a rigorous assessment of gene 
function. It will allow subtle but important phenotypes to be 
identified: an important capability because we already know 
that knock-out mutants often lack obvious phenotypes, 
implying that the functions of many genes will only become 
apparent after a more detailed analysis at a range of levels 
and in a range of conditions. It will allow us to generate a 
data bank that contains a rich collection of information at 
different levels of organisation, giving novel and exciting 
possibilities for multi-dimensional data mining.
</p>
<p>Third, the defined conditions, technical capacity and 
accumulation of knowledge will provide a unique opportunity 
to exploit undirected and directed genetic diversity 
generated in the other 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> network. They will allow efficient analysis and 
exploitation of the natural variation and novel mutations 
provided by network I, "Creation and detection of new genetic 
diversity". A close interaction will emerge with network II, 
"Protein Communities", especially during functional analysis 
of transformants with altered expression of membrane proteins 
and altered expression of transcription factors.
</p>
