<H4>
<A NAME="afgn" HREF="http://www.uni-tuebingen.de/plantphys/AFGN/">

<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Functional Genomics Network
</A> (AFGN)
</H4>
<p>As the result of a 10-year international effort, the first 
genome of a green plant, 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I>, was 
<A HREF="http://www.nsf.gov/od/lpa/news/press/00/pr0094.htm">
completely sequenced
</A> by the end of 2000. In expectation of this event, the 
<A HREF="http://www.nsf.gov/">
National Science Foundation USA
</A> (NSF) sponsored a workshop at the Salk Institute 
(January 2000) to discuss goals of a 10 year follow-up 
project. As a consequence, an NSF program was initiated to 
determine the function of all 25,000 

<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genes "within their cellular, organismal and 
evolutionary context" by the year 2010 (<A 
HREF="/portals/masc/workshop2010.jsp">The 2010 project
</A>). The outline of the NSF project states very clearly 
that the "
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> research community has become a model of international 
research collaboration. It is expected that continued efforts 
by the international community of scientists will be 
essential for the success of the 2010 Project." This 
statement acknowledged that the successful completion of the 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genome sequence was based on contributions by scientists 
not only from the USA, but also from many European countries 
and Japan. Among these, a particularly important German 
contribution were the gene annotation efforts by 
<A HREF="http://mips.gsf.de/">
MIPS
</A> based in Munich.
</p>
<p>This international background and the enthusiasm about the 
new, revolutionary possibilities of plant research in a 
network with tight international cooperation triggered a 
group of plant biologists in Germany to elaborate a proposal 
for a 10-year German 

<A HREF="http://www.uni-tuebingen.de/plantphys/AFGN/">

<I>Arabidopsis
</I> Functional Genomics Network
</A> (AFGN). Coordinator of the network is Klaus Harter.
</p><p>Contact:<A HREF="mailto:klaus.harter.uni-tuebingen.de">
Dr. Klaus Harter</A>
<br><A HREF="http://www.uni-tuebingen.de/plantphys/">www.uni-tuebingen.de/plantphys</A>
<br>ZMBP/Plant Physiology
<br>University of Tubingen
<br>Auf der Morgenstelle 1
<br>Tubingin, Germany

<br>
<p>Functional analysis of multiprotein families was agreed 
upon as the central topic for initial 
grant applications to the 
<A HREF="http://www.uni-tuebingen.de/plantphys/AFGN/">
AFGN
</A>. This includes the analysis of all members of a given 
multi-protein family with respect to their expression and 
function during the 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> life cycle. From the very beginning, all essential 
aspects of the German initiative including the scientific 
aims, details of the organisation as well as essential 
aspects of the timing and tight international integration 
were discussed in the context of the 
<A HREF="/portals/masc/workshop2010.jsp">
NSF 2010 Project
</A>. One of the central tenets of this NSF project and one 
of the main reasons why 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> research has been so successful in the past decade, is 
that any new tools and new knowledge derived during the 
project are made available to the community in a timely 
manner and without restrictions.

</p> 
<p>The second funding period of the AFGN will end in the fall of 2007. 
The DFG has announced that it will continue to support German 
<I>Arabidopsis</I> functional genomics research and German/US 
cooperation within the framework of the AFGN. 
 <B><a 
href="http://www.dfg.de/en/news/information_science_research/internation
al_focus/info_wissenschaft_39_06.html">
(The announcement of the
third funding period is available at the DFG site by clicking here)</a></B>

<p><b>Future support will concentrate on two areas of research:</b>

<dl>
<I>Functional Genomics of Biological Processes</I><br>
Research in the AFGN has shown that different members of a given 
<I>Arabidopsis</I> multiprotein family may be multifunctional and, thus, 
may play a role in different biological processes and pathways. As a 
consequence, the focus of AFGN will move from a sole multiprotein 
family-based genomic approach towards the genomic analysis of multigene 
networks whose members functionally interact with each other in 
accomplishing a given biological process.<p>
<dl>

<I>Tools and Resources for Plant Functional Genomic Research</I><br>
There is still demand for the development of novel and genome-wide tools 
and technologies and additional resources in plant functional genomics 
to address unmet needs. It is expected that these methods and tools will 
complement the already existing tools and research resources, will 
provide quantitative readouts, will be cost effective and comprehensive, 
and, thus, will be readily adopted by the scientific community.<br>
		
</dl>
